NumPy¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
In [2]:

In [3]:
x.shape
Out[3]:
(2, 3)
In [4]:
x[:, 0] #all row elements of the 0th column
Out[4]:
array([1, 4])
In [5]:
x[0,:] # all column elements of the first row
Out[5]:
array([1, 2, 3])
In [6]:
x[:,1]
Out[6]:
array([2, 5])

Linear algebra¶

In [20]:
#Orthornormal vectors of \mathbb{R}^3
e1 = np.eye(1, 3)
e2 = np.eye(1,3, k=1)
e3 = np.eye(1, 3, k = 2)
In [21]:
np.dot(e1, e2.T) #dot acts through matrix multplication
Out[21]:
array([[0.]])
In [22]:
np.inner(e1, e2) #inner is the standard innerproduct on R^n
Out[22]:
array([[0.]])
In [23]:
np.outer(e1, e2)
Out[23]:
array([[0., 1., 0.],
       [0., 0., 0.],
       [0., 0., 0.]])
In [24]:
np.arange(len(e1))
Out[24]:
array([0])
In [25]:
B.sum(axis=0)
Out[25]:
array([3., 3.])
In [26]:
sum(B)
Out[26]:
array([3., 3.])
In [27]:
B.sum(axis=1)
Out[27]:
array([2., 2., 2.])

Plotting¶

In [28]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [29]:
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi)
y = np.sin(x)
In [30]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 4), facecolor='grey',)
fig.suptitle("Sin(x)") #this applies even if there are mutliple plots.
plt.plot(x, y)
plt.show()
plt.close()
